Current paper introduction: 
Galaxy clusters, the most massive gravitationally bound objects in the universe, serve as powerful probes of cosmology and large-scale structure formation. Their abundance and spatial distribution are highly sensitive to fundamental cosmological parameters, including the matter density and the amplitude of matter fluctuations. The thermal Sunyaev-Zel'dovich (tSZ) effect, a spectral distortion of the Cosmic Microwave Background (CMB) created by inverse Compton scattering of photons off hot electrons in the intracluster medium, provides a robust method for detecting and characterizing these structures. Because the tSZ signal is proportional to the integrated electron pressure along the line of sight, its surface brightness is nearly independent of redshift, making it an ideal tool for constructing mass-selected cluster catalogs out to high redshifts. Upcoming and ongoing surveys are poised to detect tens of thousands of clusters via the tSZ effect, promising to tighten cosmological constraints significantly.

Realizing the full potential of these surveys hinges on our ability to accurately isolate the faint tSZ signal from a complex superposition of other astrophysical and cosmological signals present in millimeter-wave observations. The primary CMB anisotropies, while dominant on large angular scales, can be separated based on their distinct blackbody spectrum. A more challenging contaminant is the Cosmic Infrared Background (CIB), the integrated emission from dusty, star-forming galaxies throughout cosmic history. The CIB is a significant source of emission at the frequencies where tSZ experiments are most sensitive. Furthermore, because these galaxies trace the same underlying dark matter distribution as galaxy clusters, the CIB is spatially correlated with the tSZ signal itself, making a simple separation based on angular morphology difficult. This contamination can introduce biases in the reconstructed tSZ map, leading to spurious detections and increased scatter in the relationship between tSZ observables and cluster mass.

A common approach to this component separation problem is the Internal Linear Combination (ILC) method, which constructs a weighted sum of multi-frequency maps to minimize the total variance in the final map while preserving the signal of interest. While powerful, standard ILC techniques can be suboptimal, as they often treat foregrounds as contaminants to be deterministically nulled. Such hard constraints can lead to an undesirable amplification of instrumental noise from frequency channels that are heavily weighted to enforce the null. Moreover, these methods may not fully exploit the rich statistical information encoded in the spatial correlations of the foregrounds themselves.

In this paper, we present a more statistically grounded approach based on a Multi-Frequency Wiener Filter (MWF). The Wiener filter is, by construction, the optimal linear estimator that minimizes the mean-squared error between the reconstructed map and the true underlying signal. Our framework leverages the complete statistical description of the sky, incorporating the full set of auto- and cross-frequency power spectra for all relevant signal and noise components. Critically, rather than attempting to project out the CIB, we explicitly model it as a source of correlated foreground noise. This allows the filter to find the statistically optimal balance between suppressing CIB contamination, preserving the tSZ signal, and minimizing instrumental noise amplification. We apply this MWF to simulated multi-frequency observations representative of the Simons Observatory and Planck, reconstruct the tSZ Compton-$y$ map, and perform a comprehensive cluster detection analysis. By comparing the resulting cluster catalog's purity and completeness to that derived from a conventional ILC method, we demonstrate that a full statistical treatment of foregrounds is essential for robustly extracting faint cosmological signals and maximizing the scientific return of next-generation CMB surveys.

